1. Early Roman Comedy. Roman like Greek Comedy may be traced back to the Harvest, Vintage and other Festivals. ‘The joy os harvest' found expression in alternate verses, singer answering singer, at first playful, but gradually becoming so personal and bitter as finally to call for the inter— serence of the law. Hence sprang the versus Fescennini which are said to derive their name from the South Etrurian town Fescennium. Their mette was the Saturnian, the one national Roman product in matters rhythmical, a mixture of the iambic and trochaic rhythm. The Italian habit of rivals improvising verses always has been, and still is, a favourite entertainment among Italian rustics.

A pestilence at Rome in the consulship of C. Sulpicius Paeticus . and C. Licinius Stolo Β. C. 364 led to the invitation of Etruscan players (ludiones) who introduced the mimic dance without words but with flute-accompaniment.
